Syllabus - Assignment Weights¶

Course Goals¶

To understand the difference between the different types of data (structured, semi-structured, unstructured, and metadata) and how this impacts underlying storage mechanisms.

Be able to select and implement the optimal data management system and associated workflow as a function of the datas Volume, Velocity, Variety, and Veracity.

To construct and perform queries to select data for assembly into an analysis workflow for data science.

To understand the need for and to use an available tool to carry out data cleaning and other data pre-processing activities in preparing data resources integrated from various sources.

To understand common patterns of data flow through data science analysis workflows, such as big data processing patterns using a parallel processing paradigm such as map-reduce.

To understand and compare common data visualization methods for data science.

Ref right image

The 4 V's of Big Data¶

Volume: The size of the dataset.

  • At this point > terabyte, petabyte.

Velocity: The speed at which data are generated.

  • Typically requires distinct processing approach.

Variety: Data come from multiple sources.

  • Google ranks all pages on the internet.

Veracity: The quality of data.

  • High veracity: valuable for analysis, e.g. well controlled experimental observations
  • Low veracity: lots of low-value "noise"

Ref: https://www.bigdataframework.org/the-four-vs-of-big-data/

Data Science Problem Types¶

Descriptive - Summarize a dataset

Exploratory - Find patterns, trends, or relationships in a dataset.

  • "Hypothesis generation" e.g. Spurious Correlations!

Inferential - Does your data represent a larger population?

  • Understanding bias and causes.

Ref: The Art of Data Science

Data Science Problem Types¶

Predictive - Given a set of input variables, generate a "better than random" guess of the output value. e.g. Regression Analysis

  • Causal - Finding the input variable that changes the output value.

Mechanistic - Finding the underlying mechanism that drives the output value given certain input bariables.

  • Singapore's Circle Line Train
  • Medium: How the Circle Line rogue train was caught with data
  • The first link goes to the git repo. The second link goes to medium, search "circle line train" on the right. It's a great example of both analysis and how to communicate complex data science problems.

Data Types¶

Structured Data: Data that fit a predefined model or format for straightforward analysis.

  • Requires or assumes a data model
  • See: Tidy Data (for R)

Semi-Structured Data: Data that do not fit a predefined model, but can be parsed to fit a data model or format.

  • Think JSON, BSON, XML, HTML, etc.
  • See: Data Wrangling

Ref: https://www.bigdataframework.org/data-types-structured-vs-unstructured-data/

Data Types¶

Unstructured Data: Data that do not fit a predefined model.

  • Think: emails, text files, audio/video, social media, mobile data, books, etc.

Metadata: Data about data.

  • Usually some of the most important data youll work with!

Ref: https://www.bigdataframework.org/data-types-structured-vs-unstructured-data/

Data Storage¶

The type and end use of data dictate how it is stored and processed.

Structured Query Language (SQL) Best for storing structured and semi-structured data.

Non-Structured Query Language (NoSQL) Best for storing unstructured data.

Ref: https://www.bigdataframework.org/data-types-structured-vs-unstructured-data/

https://mrsaeeddev.medium.com/learn-how-to-store-data-for-your-data-science-problems-even-if-you-dont-want-to-27e02dd9f781

Moving Data: ETL¶

The process of accessing, shaping, and inserting data within a data science workflow is referred to ETL or: Extract: Obtaining data from (typically heterogeneous) source(s) in preparation for use in a data science workflow.

  • API Call
  • Web Scraping
  • Historical Document Analysis

Transform: Shaping data into a useable (temporary) format (schema).

  • Missing Values/Sentinel Values
  • Feature Engineering

Load: Writing processed data to a target database.

ETL Pipeline: the workflow (programmatic) for doing ETL.

Ref: https://www.databricks.com/glossary/extract-transform-load

Data Access¶

The type and end use of data dictate how it is accessed (efficiently)

Search Engine Good for text queries.

  • Google Cloud Search, Elastic Search, Apache Solr

Document Store Flexible schema.

  • Amazon DynamoDB, Mongo DB, Apache Couch DB

Columnar Store Good for single column queries and value aggregations.

  • Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, Apache HBase

Ref: https://www.toptal.com/data-science/data-engineering-guide-to-storages

Data Visualization¶

"Simple design, intense content" - Edward Tufte

The Visual Display of Quantitative Information

Convey the content of the data in a manner sufficient to inspire action. -me

Carte figurative des pertes successives en hommes de lArme Franaise dans la campagne de Russie 1812-1813.

Charles Joseph Minard, 1869

This iconic image was created to force a revisionist public to remember the costs of war.

On the Mode of Communication of Cholera

John Snow, 1854

This iconic image assisted the identification of a communal water pump contaminated with Cholera.

Notes on matters affecting the health, efficiency, and hospital administration of the British Army : founded chiefly on the experience of the late war / by Florence Nightingale ; presented by request to the Secretary of State for War

Florence Nightingale, 1858

The Rose Diagram identified epidemic diseases as the prevailing cause of death during the Crimean War and persuaded the use of sanitary controls to address them.

Out of Sight, Out of Mind: A Visualization of Drone Strikes in Pakistan Since 2004. Pitch Interactive, 2015

This modern interactive visualization galvanized public opinion about the expanding use of drone strikes in Pakistan under President Obama.

Computing Optimal Road Trips on a Limited Budget

Ronald S. Olson, 2016

This blog post comparatively explained the use of a genetic algorithm and multi-objective pareto optimization to find the shortest route to visit 48 state capitols in 8 days using the Google Maps API. These are popular techniques for optimizing business problems.
